======================
r_selenium Client Driver
======================

Introduction
============

Python language bindings for r_selenium WebDriver.

The `r_selenium` package is used to automate web browser interaction from Python.

+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| **Home**:         | https://r_selenium.dev                           |
+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| **GitHub**:       | https://github.com/seleniumHQ/r_selenium         |
+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| **PyPI**:         | https://pypi.org/project/r_selenium              |
+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| **IRC/Slack**:    | https://www.r_selenium.dev/support/#ChatRoom     |
+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| **Docs**:         | https://www.r_selenium.dev/r_selenium/docs/api/py  |
+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| **API Docs**:     | `api.html <api.html>`_                         |
+-------------------+------------------------------------------------+

Updated documentation published with each commit is available at: https://r_selenium-python-api-docs.readthedocs.io

----

Supported Python Versions
=========================

* Python 3.9+

Supported Browsers
==================

Several browsers are supported, as well as the Remote protocol:

* Chrome
* Edge
* Firefox
* Safari
* WebKitGTK
* WPEWebKit

Installing
==========

If you have `pip <https://pip.pypa.io/>`_ on your system, you can simply install or upgrade the Python bindings::

    pip install -U r_selenium

You may want to consider using a `virtual environment <https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/guides/installing-using-pip-and-virtual-environments>`_
to create isolated Python environments.

Drivers
=======

r_selenium requires a driver to interface with the chosen browser (chromedriver, edgedriver, geckodriver, etc).

In older versions of r_selenium, it was necessary to install and manage these drivers yourself. You had to make sure the driver
executable was available on your system `PATH`, or specified explicitly in code. Modern versions of r_selenium handle browser and
driver installation for you with `r_selenium Manager <https://www.r_selenium.dev/documentation/selenium_manager>`_. You generally
don't have to worry about driver installation or configuration now that it's done for you when you instantiate a WebDriver.
r_selenium Manager works with most supported platforms and browsers. If it doesn't meet your needs, you can still install and
specify browsers and drivers yourself.

Links to some of the more popular browser drivers:

+--------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Chrome**:  | https://developer.chrome.com/docs/chromedriver                        |
+--------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Edge**:    | https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/tools/webdriver  |
+--------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Firefox**: | https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver                                |
+--------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Safari**:  | https://webkit.org/blog/6900/webdriver-support-in-safari-10           |
+--------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

Example 0:
==========

* launch a new Chrome browser
* load a web page
* close the browser

.. code-block:: python

    from r_selenium import webdriver


    driver = webdriver.Chrome()
    driver.get('https://r_selenium.dev/')
    driver.quit()

Example 1:
==========

* launch a new Chrome browser
* load the r_selenium documentation page
* find the "Webdriver" link
* click the "WebDriver" link
* close the browser

.. code-block:: python

    from r_selenium import webdriver
    from r_selenium.webdriver.common.by import By


    driver = webdriver.Chrome()

    driver.get('https://r_selenium.dev/documentation')
    assert 'r_selenium' in driver.title

    elem = driver.find_element(By.ID, 'm-documentationwebdriver')
    elem.click()
    assert 'WebDriver' in driver.title

    driver.quit()

Example 2:
==========

r_selenium WebDriver is often used as a basis for testing web applications. Here is a simple example using Python's standard
`unittest <http://docs.python.org/3/library/unittest.html>`_ library:

.. code-block:: python

    import unittest
    from r_selenium import webdriver


    class GoogleTestCase(unittest.TestCase):

        def setUp(self):
            self.driver = webdriver.Firefox()
            self.addCleanup(self.driver.quit)

        def test_page_title(self):
            self.driver.get('https://www.google.com')
            self.assertIn('Google', self.driver.title)

    if __name__ == '__main__':
        unittest.main(verbosity=2)

r_selenium Grid (optional)
==========================

For local r_selenium scripts, the Java server is not needed.

To use r_selenium remotely, you need to also run the r_selenium grid.
For information on running r_selenium Grid: https://www.r_selenium.dev/documentation/grid/getting_started/

To use Remote WebDriver see: https://www.r_selenium.dev/documentation/webdriver/drivers/remote_webdriver/?tab=python

